text: Yeah, it's a good question. I'm not 100% sure that it's stagnated and that we have seen some innovation. We talked before about the move from the sleeve or the top down more toward the bottom up. That certainly has been one. There are a lot of strategies that are stuck in the past, I will admit that. But going forward, people always ask me, are there additional factors out there that we're going to discover? Maybe, but I wouldn't necessarily bet on that. What I am 100% sure about is the definition that we utilize today to quantify a factor may be quite different five years or 10 years from now. I always say that factors are a fluid concept. Value is a great example of this. We already said in 1993, if I'm a French, use book-to-market, price-to-book ratios to quantify value. Today, the whole concept of book value doesn't mean the same thing that it did in 1993. It's a different concept. It's a different concept. It's a different concept. It's a different concept. It's a different concept. It's a different concept. It's a different concept. We're moving from an asset-heavy to an asset-light kind of economy. Our valuation metrics have to adjust to that transition as well. We have very different accounting rules in place today than we did 10 or 20 years ago. Our factor definitions have to adjust for that. For example, we have operating leases coming on balance sheets globally, something on the order of $3 trillion in operating leases. All this off-balance sheet financing, I take it as a very important factor. I take it as a very important factor. I take it as a very important factor. I take it as a very important factor. I take it as a very important factor. coming on to balance sheets, now messing up our view of interest rate sensitivity of those balance sheets, all kinds of other things as well. There's these innovations that occur, and a number of them occur every year that we have to be cognizant of. As better data becomes available, you're going to see some of these factors evolve in terms of their definition. That's one consideration. Another consideration, I think this is very important, is that today, especially in the retail space, factors are primarily employed as a means to beat a cap-weighted benchmark, to outperform a benchmark. I'm not convinced that that's the highest and best use of factors. Certainly in application, no question. But if you go back to the original research on factors, it really stems from an asset allocation decision, meaning that it's not about fulfilling your equity bucket with a multi-factor strategy. That's great. But if you go back to the original research on factors, it's not about fulfilling your equity bucket with a multi-factor strategy. Believe me, I would advocate for that. But if you can break apart your portfolio into the key drivers of risk and return being factors, and allocate to the factors rather than allocating to asset classes, which are nothing but a combination of these factors, you get a much better result. We're seeing some of our forward-thinking clients typically more on the larger end of the spectrum, but doing this kind of work, meaning that they're employing factors more in the asset class. That's a good point. I think that's a good point. And so I think it's really important to talk about these two ideas. And how you can support them in these two areas. And that's the way to do it. And then the last but certainly not least is this ESG factor synthesis. We're only starting down this path. I believe that these two ideas really can go hand in hand, in that both can be implemented quantitatively. Both are implemented in, call it a similar scoring methodology. Both suffer from the problems that we've talked about. The problems that we've talked about in the past, and the problems that the last hour in unintended bets, portfolio construction. So we can bring these two ideas together and produce some really cool stuff. So I think that it's just the beginning. Over the next several years, we're going to see a lot more innovation on the factor ESG synthesis front.
